🚀 Day 16: Install and Configure Nginx as a Load Balancer (LBR)
📌 Project Overview

In this lab, we configured an Nginx Load Balancer (LBR) to distribute incoming traffic across multiple backend 
application servers in a high-availability setup within the Nautilus infrastructure.

The goal was to improve performance, scalability, and fault tolerance as application traffic increased.

🏗️ Architecture Design
                Users
                  │
                  │  http://stlb01:80
                  ▼
        ┌─────────────────────┐
        │   NGINX LBR (stlb01)│
        └─────────────────────┘
            │       │       │
            ▼       ▼       ▼
     stapp01    stapp02    stapp03
     (Apache)   (Apache)   (Apache)
        │          │          │
     Port 3000  Port 3000  Port 3000

🎯 Objectives
Install Nginx on the Load Balancer server (stlb01)
Configure Nginx as a reverse proxy load balancer
Ensure traffic is distributed across multiple app servers
Validate high availability setup using curl

⚙️ Prerequisites
All app servers (stapp01, stapp02, stapp03) are running Apache
Apache is running on port 3000
No changes should be made to Apache configuration
SSH access to all servers

🧪 Implementation Steps
🟢 Step 1: Verify Apache on App Servers
sudo systemctl status httpd
sudo ss -tulnp | grep 3000

Ensure Apache is active and listening on port 3000.

🟢 Step 2: Install Nginx on Load Balancer
sudo yum install nginx -y

Enable and start service:

sudo systemctl enable nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
🟢 Step 3: Configure Nginx Load Balancer

Edit main configuration file:

sudo vi /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
🟢 Step 4: Add Upstream Configuration

Inside http {} block:

upstream app_servers {
    server stapp01:3000;
    server stapp02:3000;
    server stapp03:3000;
}
🟢 Step 5: Configure Proxy Server Block

Replace or modify server {} block:

server {
    listen 80;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://app_servers;

        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    }
}
🟢 Step 6: Validate Configuration
sudo nginx -t

Expected output:

syntax is ok
test is successful
🟢 Step 7: Restart Nginx
sudo systemctl restart nginx
🟢 Step 8: Test Load Balancer

Run multiple curl requests:

curl http://stlb01:80
curl http://stlb01:80
curl http://stlb01:80

You should see responses rotating between:

stapp01
stapp02
stapp03

🧠 Key Learnings
Nginx can act as a reverse proxy + load balancer
upstream defines backend server pool
proxy_pass connects traffic to backend group
Load balancing improves:
Availability
Performance
Scalability

⚠️ Common Mistakes
Forgetting to add proxy_pass
Using wrong backend port
Editing wrong Nginx config file
Not restarting Nginx after changes
Assuming Apache runs on port 80

